ODE XVII.

Horace here predicts the glory and immortality of his name. And with the true spirit of a poet he imagines himself al- ready assuming the form and facultIes of a swan, and soar- rng above the earth, over which he is about to take his aeria] flight. As he will leave the humble abodes of men, so he will shake off “this mortal coil,” and cease to be an obJect of human sympathy or sorrow. He wishes not for the empty hon- ours of a burial, nor the waste of useless tears on his account, Since he shall not die.
